The Foundation — DataSource & Connection Pooling:
    Everything in Spring Data Access starts with a DataSource. 
    It's the factory that produces JDBC connections. 
    Spring never manages raw DriverManager.getConnection() calls directly — it always goes through a DataSource.
Three common implementations:
      DriverManagerDataSource — creates a new connection every call; for testing only
      HikariCP — the Spring Boot default; fastest, production-grade connection pool
      Apache DBCP2 — older but still widely used
In Spring Boot, you configure it via application.properties:
    spring.datasource.url=jdbc:postgresql://localhost/mydb
    spring.datasource.username=user
    spring.datasource.password=pass
    spring.datasource.hikari.maximum-pool-size=10

Modules in Spring Data Access:
  1. JDBC Module - Simplifies JDBC operations
    Spring JDBC wraps raw JDBC and eliminates the boilerplate 
    (open connection → create statement → execute → map results → close everything → handle checked exceptions).
    The key class is JdbcTemplate.
    JdbcTemplate:
        @Repository
        public class UserDao {
            private final JdbcTemplate jdbc;
            // query → returns list
            public List<User> findAll() {
                return jdbc.query("SELECT * FROM users", new BeanPropertyRowMapper<>(User.class));
            }
            // queryForObject → returns single row
            public User findById(Long id) {
                return jdbc.queryForObject("SELECT * FROM users WHERE id=?",
                    new BeanPropertyRowMapper<>(User.class), id);
            }
            // update → INSERT / UPDATE / DELETE
            public int save(String name) {
                return jdbc.update("INSERT INTO users(name) VALUES(?)", name);
            }
        }
    RowMapper is the interface that maps a single ResultSet row to an object.
            BeanPropertyRowMapper does this automatically by matching column names to field names.
            You implement RowMapper<T> manually for custom logic.
    NamedParameterJdbcTemplate
            Uses :name style parameters instead of ? — much cleaner for queries with many parameters:
            Map<String, Object> params = Map.of("name", "Alice", "age", 30);
            jdbc.query("SELECT * FROM users WHERE name=:name AND age=:age", params, rowMapper);
    SimpleJdbcInsert / SimpleJdbcCall
            Higher-level helpers for inserts and stored procedure calls:
            SimpleJdbcInsert insert = new SimpleJdbcInsert(dataSource)
                .withTableName("users")
                .usingGeneratedKeyColumns("id");
            Number key = insert.executeAndReturnKey(Map.of("name", "Bob"));
    Spring JDBC also gives you a consistent exception hierarchy — 
        it translates all vendor-specific SQLExceptions into Spring's DataAccessException 
          subclasses (DuplicateKeyException, DataIntegrityViolationException, etc.), 
            so your code doesn't leak JDBC concerns.
    ✔ Features: Removes boilerplate, Handles connection closing and Exception handling
    Use Case: Simple queries and Performance-critical apps

  2.ORM Module - 
        JPA (Java Persistence API) is the specification. 
        Hibernate is the most popular implementation.
        Spring ORM integrates them, and Spring Data JPA adds repositories on top.
        Purpose :Object ↔ Table mapping and Reduce SQL usage
        Features : Session management, Lazy loading and Caching
        Use Case: Complex domain models and Enterprise applications
