SessionFactory — Lifetime and Creation
    SessionFactory is created once at application startup and lives for the entire application lifetime.
    It is thread-safe and expensive to build — 
            it reads all entity mappings, validates them against the schema, builds the SQL templates, 
            and sets up the second-level cache.
   ✔ Responsibilities: Create sessions, Maintain cache and Store ORM mappings
    In modern Spring Boot you never build it manually.
    Spring Boot auto-configures it via HibernateJpaAutoConfiguration. 
    If you need to customize it:
            @Configuration
            public class HibernateConfig {
                @Bean
                public LocalContainerEntityManagerFactoryBean entityManagerFactory(
                        DataSource dataSource) {
                    LocalContainerEntityManagerFactoryBean factory =
                        new LocalContainerEntityManagerFactoryBean();
                    factory.setDataSource(dataSource);
                    factory.setPackagesToScan("com.example.entities");
                    factory.setJpaVendorAdapter(new HibernateJpaVendorAdapter());
                    Properties props = new Properties();
                    props.put("hibernate.hbm2ddl.auto", "validate");
                    props.put("hibernate.show_sql", "true");
                    props.put("hibernate.format_sql", "true");
                    props.put("hibernate.dialect", "org.hibernate.dialect.PostgreSQLDialect");
                    props.put("hibernate.jdbc.batch_size", "50");          // batch inserts
                    props.put("hibernate.cache.use_second_level_cache", "true");
                    factory.setJpaProperties(props);
                    return factory; // this IS your SessionFactory under the hood
                }
            }

Session — Lifetime and the Three Management Strategies
          A Session is short-lived, cheap, and not thread-safe. 
          One session per request/transaction is the rule. 
          How that session gets opened and closed is the "session management" question.
          ✔ Responsibilities: CRUD operations, Manage entity lifecycle, First-level cache and Dirty checking
  Strategy 1 — Spring-managed (the standard, use this always)
      @Transactional is the trigger.
          When the proxy intercepts a method call, it asks the JpaTransactionManager to begin a transaction,
              which opens a Session and binds it to the current thread.
          When the method exits, the transaction manager commits (or rolls back), flushes the session, and closes it. 
          You never touch the session directly.
            @Service
            @Transactional          // all methods in this class get a session automatically
            public class OrderService {
                @PersistenceContext
                private EntityManager em; // Spring injects a thread-bound proxy — safe to use as field
                public Order findOrder(Long id) {
                    return em.find(Order.class, id); // session is already open, bound to this thread
                }
                public void updateStatus(Long id, String status) {
                    Order o = em.find(Order.class, id);
                    o.setStatus(status);
                    // NO explicit save needed — dirty checking detects the change and flushes on commit
                }
            }
    Strategy 2 — getCurrentSession() (Hibernate-native, still TX-bound)
        When you inject the SessionFactory directly and call getCurrentSession(), 
        Hibernate looks up the session already bound to the current transaction thread — the exact same session that @Transactional opened.
        This is useful when you're in legacy Hibernate DAOs that haven't moved to JPA yet:
            @Repository
            public class LegacyOrderDao {
                @Autowired
                private SessionFactory sessionFactory;
                public List<Order> findPending() {
                    // requires an active @Transactional on the caller — throws if no TX exists
                    Session session = sessionFactory.getCurrentSession();
                    return session.createQuery("FROM Order o WHERE o.status = 'PENDING'", Order.class)
                                  .list();
                }
            }
        This only works because Spring's JpaTransactionManager sets up the current-session context when it starts the transaction.
        If there's no active transaction, getCurrentSession() throws HibernateException.
  Strategy 3 — openSession() (manual, rarely needed)
        Opens a brand-new session completely outside any Spring transaction management. 
        You are responsible for everything — flush, commit, close.
        Needed only for background threads, batch jobs, or scheduled tasks that run outside an HTTP request:
        try (Session session = sessionFactory.openSession()) {
            Transaction tx = session.beginTransaction();
            try {
                // your work
                session.flush();
                tx.commit();
            } catch (Exception e) {
                tx.rollback();
                throw e;
            }
        } // session.close() called automatically by try-with-resources

What happens if Session not closed? ❌ Memory leak
Session Lifecycle: OpenSession() → perform operations → flush() → close()
