                       @Entity - ✔ Marks class as a persistent entity ✔ Must have a primary key
                       @Table - ✔ Maps class to specific table ✔ Optional (default = class name)
                       @Id -✔ Primary key
                       @GeneratedValue - @GeneratedValue(strategy = GenerationType.IDENTITY) ✔ Auto-generates ID
                         Strategies:
                          IDENTITY (DB auto increment)
                          SEQUENCE
                          TABLE
                          AUTO
                       @Column -@Column(name = "user_name", nullable = false) ✔ Maps field → column ✔ Controls: name, nullable,length
                       @Transient - ✔ Not persisted in DB
                       @Lob - ✔ Large objects (BLOB/CLOB)
              Relationship mapping:
                      // One-to-many (Order → OrderItems)
                      @OneToMany(mappedBy = "order", cascade = CascadeType.ALL, orphanRemoval = true)
                      private List<OrderItem> items = new ArrayList<>();
                      // Many-to-one (OrderItem → Order)
                      @ManyToOne(fetch = FetchType.LAZY)
                      @JoinColumn(name = "order_id")   // FK column in THIS table
                      private Order order;
                      // Many-to-many
                      @ManyToMany
                      @JoinTable(name = "student_course",
                                 joinColumns = @JoinColumn(name = "student_id"),
                                 inverseJoinColumns = @JoinColumn(name = "course_id"))
                      private Set<Course> courses;
                      // One-to-one
                      @OneToOne(cascade = CascadeType.ALL)
                      @JoinColumn(name = "profile_id", referencedColumnName = "id")
                      private UserProfile profile;

                      Embeddable (value object — not a separate table):
                      @Embeddable
                      public class Address {
                          private String street;
                          private String city;
                          private String country;
                      }
                      @Embedded
                      @AttributeOverrides({
                          @AttributeOverride(name = "street", column = @Column(name = "shipping_street"))
                      })
                      private Address shippingAddress;

            Feature	                One-to-Many	                              Many-to-One
            Owner of Relationship	  Usually the "Inverse" side (mappedBy).  	Usually the Owner (holds the Foreign Key).
            Code Representation	    List<Entity> entities;	                  Entity entity;
            Fetch Strategy        	LAZY (by default)              	          EAGER (by default)
            Database Table	        Does not hold the FK column.	            Holds the FK column (e.g., dept_id).

            The Golden Rule: Always use the mappedBy attribute on the @OneToMany side. 
            This tells Java: "Hey, the Many-to-One side is the one actually in charge of the database column; just mirror what it does."

            When you set a One-to-Many relationship to FetchType.LAZY, 
            the most important thing to understand is that the data is not there when you first load the parent object. 
            Instead, Hibernate (or your JPA provider) uses "Smoke and Mirrors" to handle the missing data.
            1. The Proxy (The Placeholder) - When you fetch the parent entity (e.g., a Department), the database only runs a query for the Department table.
                                              For the List<Employee> collection, Hibernate provides a Lazy Initialization Proxy.
            2. The Database Query - The database query for the "Many" side is deferred.
            3. The "Trigger" Point - The data is only fetched when you explicitly interact with the collection. This is called "initializing the proxy."
            
            What is physically "in" the field?
            If you were to inspect the object in a debugger before it is initialized, you wouldn't see a standard java.util.ArrayList.
            Instead, you would see something like:PersistentBag or PersistentSet (internal Hibernate classes).Common triggers include:
                  Calling .size() on the list.
                  Calling .get(0).
                  Using a for loop to iterate through the collection.
                  Calling any method that requires the actual data inside the list.

          Feature       State Before Access      State After Access
          Memory Usage  Very Low                 Higher (filled with child objects)
          SQL Executed  Only Parent Query        Parent Query + Child Query
          Object Type   Hibernate Proxy Wrapper  Initialized Collection

          The Danger Zone: LazyInitializationException
          Because the proxy needs to go back to the database to get the data, it requires an active database connection (Session).
          
                If you fetch a Department, close the transaction (or return the object from a @Service to a Controller), 
                and then try to call department.getEmployees(), the application will throw a LazyInitializationException.
                The proxy tries to reach out to the database, finds the "phone line" is cut, and crashes.

        2. Entity Lifecycle States:
              An entity can be in one of four states 
              — this is fundamental to understanding what Hibernate does:
                  new object
                       ↓  persist()
                    TRANSIENT ──→ MANAGED (inside persistence context / session)
                                      ↓ evict() / clear() / close()
                                  DETACHED ──→ merge() ──→ MANAGED again
                                      ↓ remove()
                                  REMOVED (will be deleted on flush)

            Transient — just a Java object; Hibernate knows nothing about it
            Managed — inside the current Session/EntityManager; changes are tracked automatically (dirty checking)
            Detached — was managed, now outside the session (e.g. after session closed); changes NOT tracked
            Removed — scheduled for deletion on the next flush
          3. EntityManagerFactory and EntityManager:
                EntityManagerFactory - created once per application (or per persistence unit). 
                                     - expensive and thread-safe. 
                EntityManager - created per request/transaction. 
                              - cheap and NOT thread-safe.
                Relationship : EntityManagerFactory → creates → EntityManager → interacts with DB
                // Spring auto-injects a thread-safe proxy for EntityManager
                @PersistenceContext
                private EntityManager em;
                @PersistenceUnit
                private EntityManagerFactory emf;
                Spring injects a thread-bound proxy for EntityManager — 
                    each thread gets its own actual EntityManager behind the scenes. 
                    You never call emf.createEntityManager() manually in Spring.
          4. Session / EntityManager Methods
                  Method                    What it does
                  persist(entity)           Makes a transient entity managed; INSERT on flush
                  find(Class, id)           Lookup by PK; returns null if not found; checks 1st-level cache first
                  getReference(Class, id)   Returns a proxy (lazy); throws if not found when accessed
                  merge(entity)             Copies state of a detached entity into a managed instance; returns the managed copy
                  remove(entity)            Schedules a managed entity for deletion
                  flush()                   Synchronizes the persistence context with the DB right now — executes pending SQL
                  clear()                   Detaches ALL entities from the session; clears 1st-level cache
                  evict(entity)             Detaches ONE specific entity from the session
                  refresh(entity)           Re-reads state from DB, discarding unsaved changes
                  contains(entity)          Checks if entity is currently managed
                  detach(entity)            Explicitly moves an entity to detached state
                flush() vs commit: 
                        flush() sends SQL to the DB but doesn't commit the transaction. 
                        You can flush multiple times within one transaction. 
                        On commit, a flush happens automatically.
                        Full Flow (Important) : 
                            EntityManagerFactory → EntityManager → Persistence Context →flush() →DB
                clear() use case:
                      Processing large batches — 
                      flush then clear every N records to avoid the session growing unbounded:
                        for (int i = 0; i < records.size(); i++) {
                            em.persist(records.get(i));
                            if (i % 50 == 0) {
                                em.flush();
                                em.clear(); // frees memory; entities detach
                            }
                        }
                        Effect: All entities become detached and No tracking (no dirty checking)
                          User user = em.find(User.class, 1);
                          em.clear();
                          user.setName("New"); // NOT updated in DB
                          flush() vs clear()
                          Feature	      flush()    	clear()
                          Purpose	      Sync DB	    Clear cache
                          SQL execution	Yes	        No
                          Entity state	Managed	    Detached
            5. First-Level Cache (Persistence Context)
                    Every EntityManager / Session has a built-in cache scoped to the current session.
                    When you call find() twice with the same ID in the same session, Hibernate hits the DB only once — the second call returns the cached object. 
                    This cache is always on and cannot be disabled.
              Second-Level Cache is optional, shared across sessions, configured per entity with @Cache:
                        @Entity  
                        @Cache(usage = CacheConcurrencyStrategy.READ_WRITE)
                        public class Product { ... }
            6. Fetch Types
                Controls when related data is loaded:
                FetchType.LAZY (default for @OneToMany, @ManyToMany) —
                          loads related data only when you actually access it (uses a proxy). 
                          Efficient but risks LazyInitializationException if you access it after the session is closed.
                FetchType.EAGER (default for @ManyToOne, @OneToOne) — 
                          loads related data immediately with the parent. 
                          Can cause performance issues if overused.
                The N+1 Problem: 
                          If you load 100 orders with LAZY items, and then iterate and access .getItems() on each, 
                          Hibernate fires 1 query for orders + 100 queries for items = 101 queries. 
                Solutions:
                      // Solution 1: JOIN FETCH in JPQL
                      em.createQuery("SELECT o FROM Order o JOIN FETCH o.items", Order.class).getResultList();
                      // Solution 2: @EntityGraph
                      @EntityGraph(attributePaths = {"items", "customer"})
                      List<Order> findAll();
                      // Solution 3: @BatchSize (Hibernate-specific)
                      @BatchSize(size = 25) // loads 25 items at a time instead of 1
                      private List<OrderItem> items;
           7. Query Types: 
              Querying — JPQL, Criteria API, Native SQL
              JPQL (Java Persistence Query Language) — 
                  like SQL but operates on entity classes and fields, not tables and columns:
                  // TypedQuery
                          TypedQuery<Order> q = em.createQuery(
                              "SELECT o FROM Order o WHERE o.customer.name = :name AND o.total > :min",
                              Order.class);
                          q.setParameter("name", "Alice");
                          q.setParameter("min", new BigDecimal("100"));
                          List<Order> orders = q.getResultList();
                  // Named query (defined on the entity)
                          @NamedQuery(name = "Order.byStatus",
                                      query = "SELECT o FROM Order o WHERE o.status = :status")
              Criteria API —
                 type-safe, programmatic query building; verbose but refactoring-safe:                     
                    Old: Hibernate Criteria (Deprecated)
                          Criteria c = session.createCriteria(User.class);
                          c.add(Restrictions.eq("name", "Baskar"));👉 Deprecated ❌
                          Modern: JPA Criteria API
                    From JPA:
                        CriteriaBuilder cb = em.getCriteriaBuilder();
                        CriteriaQuery<User> cq = cb.createQuery(User.class);
                        Root<User> root = cq.from(User.class);
                        cq.select(root).where(cb.equal(root.get("name"), "Baskar"));
              Native SQL — 
                  when you need DB-specific features:
                      List<Object[]> rows = em.createNativeQuery(
                          "SELECT id, name FROM users WHERE name ILIKE :pattern")
                          .setParameter("pattern", "%alice%")
                          .getResultList();
          8. Cascade Types:
              Controls what happens to related entities when you do an operation on the parent:
                    Cascade      Effect
                    PERSIST      When parent is persisted, children are too
                    MERGE        When parent is merged, children are merged
                    REMOVE       When parent is removed, children are deleted
                    REFRESH      When parent is refreshed, children are too
                    DETACH       When parent is detached, children are tooALLAll of the above
              orphanRemoval = true is separate — 
              it deletes a child when it's removed from the parent's collection (not just when the parent is deleted).

