JPA Equivalents
  If you are using EntityManager (standard in Spring Data JPA), the methods have different names but the same logic:
  find() is the equivalent of get().
  getReference() is the equivalent of load().

7 core in Hibernate
1. ORM (Object-Relational Mapping)
    This is the fundamental job. Hibernate maps your Java POJOs (Plain Old Java Objects) to Database Tables.
    The Mapping: Using annotations (like @Entity, @Table, @Column) or XML,
                Hibernate understands that a class attribute like String userName corresponds to a table column USER_NAME.
    The Benefit: You work with objects and methods rather than manually mapping result sets to objects.
                  Java Object ↔ Database Table
                  Java    	DB
                  Class	    Table
                  Object	  Row
                  Field    	Column
2. SQL Generation
    Hibernate acts as a translator. You don't have to write vendor-specific SQL for every operation.
    Dialects: Hibernate uses a Dialect (e.g., PostgreSQLDialect, MySQL8Dialect) to know how to talk to your specific database.
    Automatic Creation: When you call session.save(user),
                        Hibernate automatically generates the INSERT INTO... statement for you at runtime.
3. Persistence Context (1st-Level Cache)
    The Session acts as the First-Level Cache. It is a mandatory, short-lived cache associated with the current unit of work.    
    De-duplication: If you request the same User object twice in the same session, Hibernate only hits the database once. 
                    The second time, it pulls the object from the Persistence Context.
    Scope: It is private to the current session and is destroyed when the session closes.
4. Second-Level Cache
    Unlike the first-level cache, the Second-Level Cache is SessionFactory-scoped and optional.
    Sharing: Data stored here is available across different sessions and even different users.
    External Providers: Hibernate doesn't provide the cache itself but integrates with providers like Ehcache, Infinispan, or Redis.
5. Dirty Checking
    This is a "smart" feature that minimizes database updates.
    Mechanism: When an object is loaded into the Persistence Context, Hibernate keeps a "snapshot" of its original state.
    Automatic Update: When the transaction commits, Hibernate compares the current state of the object with the snapshot. 
                    If you changed a field (e.g., user.setName("New Name")), Hibernate detects the "dirtiness" and automatically triggers an UPDATE statement. 
                    You don't need to call session.update() manually.
6. Lazy Loading via Proxies
    To save memory and improve performance, Hibernate doesn't load everything at once.
    Proxies: If a User has a list of Orders, Hibernate doesn't fetch the orders immediately.
            Instead, it places a Proxy (a placeholder object) there.
    On-Demand: The SQL query to fetch the orders is only executed the moment you actually call user.getOrders().size() or iterate through them.
7. Transaction Management
    Hibernate integrates with transaction APIs to ensure data integrity (ACID properties).
    Unit of Work: It ensures that a series of operations (like withdrawing money from one account and depositing in another) either all succeed or all fail.
    Abstraction: It abstracts the underlying JDBC transaction management, allowing you to focus on the business logic rather than connection.commit() or connection.rollback() boilerplate.

Example: 
        // 1. Start Transaction
        Transaction tx = session.beginTransaction();
        // 2. Fetch User (The Profile field is a Proxy at this point)
        User user = session.get(User.class, 1L); 
        // 3. Lazy Loading Triggered
        // The moment we call getProfile().getBio(), Hibernate fires a SELECT for the Profile table.
        String oldBio = user.getProfile().getBio();
        // 4. Dirty Checking at work
        // We simply change the Java object. We DON'T call session.update().
        user.getProfile().setBio("Updated Bio via Dirty Checking!");
        // 5. Transaction Management
        // When we commit, Hibernate:
        //   a) Performs Dirty Checking
        //   b) Sees the Bio changed
        //   c) Issues the SQL UPDATE
        //   d) Finalizes the DB transaction
        tx.commit(); 
        session.close();

Common Hibernate pitfalls:
N+1 query problem — loading a list of orders and then accessing order.getItems() in a loop fires one query for orders and then one query per order for items. 
        Fix with JOIN FETCH in your JPQL query or @EntityGraph.
LazyInitializationException — accessing a lazy relationship outside a transaction. 
        Fix by keeping data access inside @Transactional, or using FetchType.EAGER, or a DTO projection that doesn't need the relationship at all.
ddl-auto=create in production — drops and recreates all tables on startup. 
        Always use validate or none in production, and manage schema changes with Flyway or Liquibase instead.

