@transactional won’t work for private method:
  If you annotate a private method with @Transactional, Spring will simply ignore it, and no transaction will be started.  
  The reason for this lies in how Spring handles transactions under the hood using AOP (Aspect-Oriented Programming) Proxies.
  1. The Proxy Mechanism:
        When you use @Transactional, Spring doesn't actually modify your class code. Instead, it creates a Proxy object that wraps your bean.
        When a caller invokes a method, they are actually calling the Proxy.
        The Proxy starts the transaction, then calls the "real" method in your bean.
        After the real method finishes, the Proxy commits or rolls back the transaction.
        The Catch: For the Proxy to intercept the call, the method must be public.
                  A Proxy cannot "see" or override a private method from the outside.
  2. The "Self-Invocation" Problem
      Even if your method is public, @Transactional will fail if you call it from within the same class.
      @Service
      public class UserService {
          public void registerUser() {
              // This call stays INSIDE the 'this' object.
              // It bypasses the Proxy, so NO transaction starts!
              saveData(); 
          }
          @Transactional
          public void saveData() { 
              // Database logic here
          }
      }
      Because registerUser() calls saveData() directly (using the this reference), the Proxy is never triggered. 
      To Spring, it looks like a standard Java method call.
  3. How to Fix It
      If you find yourself needing a transaction on a private method, you have three main options: 
      A. Refactor to Public (Most Common)
        Make the method public and call it from a different bean (e.g., call ServiceB.method() from ServiceA). 
        This ensures the call goes through the Proxy.
      B. Use Programmatic Transactions
        If you absolutely must keep the logic inside a private method or the same class, use TransactionTemplate.
        This does not rely on Proxies or visibility.
            @Autowired
            private TransactionTemplate transactionTemplate;
            private void myPrivateMethod() {
                transactionTemplate.execute(status -> {
                    // Your transactional code goes here
                    return null;
                });
            }
      C. Self-Injection (The "Hack")
          You can inject a bean into itself. This forces the call to go through the Proxy even when calling a method in the same class.
          Note: This is generally considered a "code smell" and should be avoided if possible.
          @Service
          public class UserService {
              @Autowired
              private UserService self; // Injecting the proxy of itself
              public void start() {
                  self.saveData(); // Now the proxy is triggered!
              }
              @Transactional
              public void saveData() { ... }
          }
Summary Checklist:
    For @Transactional to work, the method must be:
    Public (not private, protected, or package-private).
    Called from an external bean (not a local call within the same class).
    In a Spring-managed Bean (annotated with @Service, @Component, etc.).

@Transactional gotcha — self-invocation
    If method A calls method B in the same class, and B is @Transactional, 
                    Spring's proxy is bypassed — B's transaction annotation has NO effect. 
    Solution: inject the bean into itself, or restructure into separate beans.

  Transaction Propagation -  Defines how transactions behave when methods call each other
        Syntax
        @Transactional(propagation = Propagation.REQUIRED)
    Types
  🔹 REQUIRED (Default) -If transaction exists → use it  Else → create new
  🔹 REQUIRES_NEW - Always create new transaction  and Suspend existing one
  🔹 SUPPORTS - Use existing if present  Else → run without transaction
  🔹 NOT_SUPPORTED - Run without transaction  Suspend existing
  🔹 MANDATORY- Must have transaction  Else → exception
  🔹 NEVER - Must NOT have transaction  Else → exception
  🔹 NESTED - Uses savepoints (partial rollback)
  
  Isolation Levels (Data Consistency) - Defines how transactions see data
     Syntax
          @Transactional(isolation = Isolation.READ_COMMITTED)
     Levels
  🔹 READ_UNCOMMITTED - Dirty reads allowed
  🔹 READ_COMMITTED (Default) -No dirty reads
  🔹 REPEATABLE_READ -Same data on repeated reads
  🔹 SERIALIZABLE -Strictest (like single-thread)
    Level                    Dirty Read     Non-repeatable Read    Phantom Read
    READ_UNCOMMITTED        ✓ possible      ✓ possible            ✓ possible
    READ_COMMITTED(default)    ✗            ✓ possible            ✓ possible
    REPEATABLE_READ            ✗                ✗                 ✓ possible
    SERIALIZABLE                ✗                ✗                    ✗
I. Read Uncommitted
      This is the lowest level.
      A transaction can read data that has been modified by another transaction but not yet committed.
      Anomaly: Dirty Reads. 
              If Transaction A changes a value and Transaction B reads it,
              but Transaction A then rolls back, Transaction B is left with "garbage" data that never technically existed.
      Use Case: Very rare; used only when speed is more important than accuracy (e.g., counting approximate page views).
II. Read Committed (Default for PostgreSQL, SQL Server, Oracle)
    A transaction can only read data that has been formally committed.
    Anomaly solved: Dirty Reads.
    New Anomaly: Non-Repeatable Reads. 
                If you read a row twice in the same transaction, a different transaction could have updated and committed it in between,
                giving you two different results for the same query.
III. Repeatable Read (Default for MySQL/InnoDB)
    This level guarantees that if you read a row, you will get the same result every time you read it again during that transaction.
    Anomaly solved: Non-Repeatable Reads.
    New Anomaly: Phantom Reads. 
            While existing rows are "locked," another transaction could insert a new row that matches your search criteria. 
            When you run the query again, a "phantom" row suddenly appears.
IV. Serializable
    The highest level.
    It simulates transactions running one after another (sequentially) rather than at the same time.
    Anomaly solved: Everything (including Phantoms).   
    Cost: Massive performance hit.
          It uses heavy locking that can lead to frequent deadlocks and slow response times.

  How to use it in Spring Boot:
      You can set the isolation level directly on the @Transactional annotation.
      If you don't specify it, Spring uses the default level of your underlying database.
      @Transactional(isolation = Isolation.SERIALIZABLE)
      public void highlyCriticalUpdate() {
          // This will be very safe but very slow
      }
  4. Why not always use Serializable?
      It's tempting to want 100% safety, 
      but in a high-traffic app, Serializable is usually a disaster.
      Locking: It places locks on ranges of data, causing other users to wait.
      Throughput: Your database capacity will drop significantly.
      Deadlocks: Because everything is waiting on everything else, the database may have to kill transactions to move forward.
      The Pro-Tip: Most developers stay with Read Committed or Repeatable Read and use Optimistic Locking (using a @Version column) 
      to handle specific conflict scenarios manually.

    How Rollback Works in @Transactional
    Default Behavior: Rollback ONLY on RuntimeException
          @Transactional
          public void transfer() {
              debit();
              credit(); // throws RuntimeException
          }
     Entire transaction rolled back
    Checked Exception Case - throw new Exception(); 👉 ❌ NO rollback by default
     ✅ Fix - @Transactional(rollbackFor = Exception.class)
     Internal Working
    Method call →Spring Proxy →Start transaction →Execute method →If exception: rollback Else: commit

