1. Projection Optimization
The core problem: 
      by default, JPA loads entire entity objects — every column, every mapped field —
            even when you only need two or three values. 
      Projections let you fetch exactly the shape of data you need.
    Interface Projection (Spring Data):
      The cleanest approach — define an interface with getter methods matching the fields you want, 
                              and Spring   Data generates a proxy at runtime:
              public interface UserSummary {
                  String getName();
                  String getEmail();
                  // nested — Spring joins Address automatically
                  AddressView getAddress();
                  interface AddressView {
                      String getCity();
                  }
                  // SpEL — computed at projection time
                  @Value("#{target.firstName + ' ' + target.lastName}")
                  String getFullName();
              }
              public interface UserRepository extends JpaRepository<User, Long> {
                  List<UserSummary> findByActiveTrue();
                  // Spring generates: SELECT u.name, u.email, a.city FROM users u LEFT JOIN addresses a ...
              }
              The SQL generated only selects the columns you declare getters for.
              No SELECT *, no hydrating a full User entity, no dirty checking overhead.
    DTO / Class Projection (JPQL constructor expression):
       When you want a concrete class (records work perfectly here):
            public record UserSummaryDto(String name, String email, String city) {}
          // In repository:
          @Query("""
              SELECT new com.example.dto.UserSummaryDto(u.name, u.email, a.city)
              FROM User u JOIN u.address a
              WHERE u.active = true
          """)
          List<UserSummaryDto> findActiveSummaries();
          The new keyword in JPQL is a constructor call — 
              Hibernate calls the matching constructor on each row.
              Records are ideal here because they give you an immutable DTO with no boilerplate.
    Dynamic Projection:
        One repository method, caller decides the return shape:
            public interface UserRepository extends JpaRepository<User, Long> {
                <T> List<T> findByDepartment(String dept, Class<T> type);
            }
            // Caller decides at runtime:
            List<UserSummary> light  = repo.findByDepartment("Engineering", UserSummary.class);
            List<User>        full   = repo.findByDepartment("Engineering", User.class);
        This is powerful for APIs that serve different consumers —
          a list endpoint needs a summary, a detail endpoint needs the full entity, same underlying query.
    @SqlResultSetMapping for Native Queries
        When you need raw SQL but still want DTO mapping:
        @SqlResultSetMapping(
            name = "UserStatMapping",
            classes = @ConstructorResult(
                targetClass = UserStatDto.class,
                columns = {
                    @ColumnResult(name = "username", type = String.class),
                    @ColumnResult(name = "order_count", type = Long.class),
                    @ColumnResult(name = "total_spent", type = BigDecimal.class)
                }
            )
        )
        @Entity public class User { ... } // mapping lives on the entity
        // Usage:
        List<UserStatDto> stats = em.createNativeQuery(
            "SELECT u.username, COUNT(o.id) AS order_count, SUM(o.total) AS total_spent " +
            "FROM users u LEFT JOIN orders o ON o.user_id = u.id GROUP BY u.username",
            "UserStatMapping"
        ).getResultList();
