Implementation — Step by Step
Step 1 — The context holder (ThreadLocal key store):
        public class DataSourceContextHolder {
            private static final ThreadLocal<String> CONTEXT = new ThreadLocal<>();
            public static void setDataSource(String key) { CONTEXT.set(key); }
            public static String getDataSource()         { return CONTEXT.get(); }
            public static void clear()                   { CONTEXT.remove(); }
            public static final String WRITE = "write";
            public static final String READ  = "read";
        }
Step 2 — The routing DataSource:
          public class RoutingDataSource extends AbstractRoutingDataSource {
              @Override
              protected Object determineCurrentLookupKey() {
                  return DataSourceContextHolder.getDataSource();
              }
          }
Step 3 — Wire up the DataSources as a map:
        @Configuration
        public class DataSourceConfig {
            @Bean
            @ConfigurationProperties("spring.datasource.write")
            public DataSource writeDataSource() { return DataSourceBuilder.create().build(); }
            @Bean
            @ConfigurationProperties("spring.datasource.read")
            public DataSource readDataSource()  { return DataSourceBuilder.create().build(); }
            @Bean
            @Primary
            public DataSource routingDataSource(
                    @Qualifier("writeDataSource") DataSource write,
                    @Qualifier("readDataSource")  DataSource read) {
                RoutingDataSource routing = new RoutingDataSource();
                routing.setTargetDataSources(Map.of(
                    DataSourceContextHolder.WRITE, write,
                    DataSourceContextHolder.READ,  read
                ));
                routing.setDefaultTargetDataSource(write); // fallback
                return routing;
            }
        }
Step 4 — AOP advice to set the key BEFORE @Transactional opens the connection:
This ordering is critical —
the DataSource key must be set before Spring's transaction manager acquires the connection, otherwise the routing is too late.
        @Aspect
        @Component
        @Order(1)  // MUST be lower (higher priority) than @Transactional's order (default 2147483647)
        public class DataSourceRoutingAspect {
            @Around("@annotation(transactional)")
            public Object route(ProceedingJoinPoint pjp,
                                org.springframework.transaction.annotation.Transactional transactional)
                    throws Throwable {
                try {
                    String key = transactional.readOnly()
                        ? DataSourceContextHolder.READ
                        : DataSourceContextHolder.WRITE;
                    DataSourceContextHolder.setDataSource(key);
                    return pjp.proceed();
                } finally {
                    DataSourceContextHolder.clear(); // always clean up ThreadLocal
                }
            }
        }
Usage — nothing changes in your service layer:
        @Service
        public class ProductService {
            @Transactional(readOnly = true)   // → read replica
            public List<Product> listAll() { return repo.findAll(); }
            @Transactional                    // → primary (write)
            public Product create(Product p)  { return repo.save(p); }
        }
      The readOnly = true flag does double duty: 
      it tells Hibernate to skip dirty checking and flush, AND your AOP advice uses it to route to the replica.                             
3. N+1 Detection in Tests
  The N+1 problem is silent in production until it breaks you.
  Catching it in tests requires intercepting Hibernate's SQL output and counting queries per test.
Approach 1 — datasource-proxy (recommended):
    datasource-proxy wraps your DataSource and fires a listener for every SQL statement executed. 
    Add it to your test scope:
        <dependency>
            <groupId>net.ttddyy</groupId>
            <artifactId>datasource-proxy</artifactId>
            <version>1.10</version>
            <scope>test</scope>
        </dependency>
    Create a test base class that counts queries:
        @SpringBootTest
        public abstract class QueryCountTestBase {
            @Autowired
            private DataSource dataSource;
            private ProxyDataSource proxyDataSource;
            @BeforeEach
            void wrapDataSource() {
                proxyDataSource = ProxyDataSourceBuilder
                    .create(dataSource)
                    .countQuery()         // enables QueryCountHolder
                    .build();
                QueryCountHolder.clear(); // reset before each test
            }
            protected void assertSelectCount(int expected) {
                QueryCount qc = QueryCountHolder.getGrandTotal();
                assertThat(qc.getSelect())
                    .as("Expected %d SELECT queries but got %d — possible N+1", expected, qc.getSelect())
                    .isEqualTo(expected);
            }
            protected void assertTotalQueryCount(int expected) {
                QueryCount qc = QueryCountHolder.getGrandTotal();
                assertThat(qc.getTotal()).isEqualTo(expected);
            }
        }
  Test a repository that might have N+1:
        class OrderRepositoryTest extends QueryCountTestBase {
        @Autowired OrderRepository orderRepo;
        @Test
        @Transactional
        void loading_orders_with_items_should_not_cause_N_plus_1() {
            // Given: 10 orders exist in test DB
            List<Order> orders = orderRepo.findAll(); // fires the initial query
            // Trigger the association — this is where N+1 would show
            orders.forEach(o -> o.getItems().size());
            // If N+1: 1 (orders) + 10 (items) = 11 queries
            // If fixed with JOIN FETCH: 1 query total
            assertSelectCount(1);
        }
    }
Approach 2 — Hibernate Statistics (no extra dependency)
    Hibernate has built-in statistics tracking — enable it in test config:
    # application-test.properties
        spring.jpa.properties.hibernate.generate_statistics=true
        spring.jpa.show-sql=true
    Assert in tests using the Statistics object:
          @SpringBootTest
          class HibernateStatisticsTest {
              @PersistenceUnit
              EntityManagerFactory emf;
              private Statistics stats;
              @BeforeEach
              void setup() {
                  stats = emf.unwrap(SessionFactory.class).getStatistics();
                  stats.setStatisticsEnabled(true);
                  stats.clear(); // reset before each test
              }
              @Test
              void findAllWithItems_shouldIssueOneQuery() {
                  List<Order> orders = orderRepo.findAllWithItems(); // your JOIN FETCH method
                  long queryCount = stats.getQueryExecutionCount();
                  assertThat(queryCount).isEqualTo(1);
                  // Also check entity fetch counts:
                  long orderFetches = stats.getEntityLoadCount();
                  System.out.println("Entities loaded: " + orderFetches);
              }
          }
Approach 3 — Log assertion with @Sql + controlled data
      For integration tests where you control the data size, you know exactly how many queries should fire.
      Pair it with a custom StatementInspector:
          public class QueryCaptor implements StatementInspector {
              private final List<String> queries = new ArrayList<>();
              @Override
              public String inspect(String sql) {
                  queries.add(sql);
                  return sql; // return unchanged — just recording
              }
              public int count() { return queries.size(); }
              public List<String> all() { return Collections.unmodifiableList(queries); }
              public void reset() { queries.clear(); }
          }
    Register it:
      // In test Hibernate config:
      props.put("hibernate.session_factory.statement_inspector",
                new QueryCaptor());
      This gives you the actual SQL strings —
      useful for asserting not just count but the shape of queries (e.g. verifying a JOIN FETCH is present).

4. Soft Deletes & Filters
      Soft delete means marking a record as deleted (via a flag or timestamp) rather than physically removing it.
      The challenge is making this transparent so every query automatically excludes "deleted" rows without you adding WHERE deleted = false everywhere.
   A. @SQLDelete + @Where (Hibernate-specific):
        @Entity
        @Table(name = "products")
        @SQLDelete(sql = "UPDATE products SET deleted_at = NOW() WHERE id = ?")
        @Where(clause = "deleted_at IS NULL")   // auto-appended to ALL queries on this entity
        public class Product {
            @Id @GeneratedValue
            private Long id;
            private String name;
            @Column(name = "deleted_at")
            private LocalDateTime deletedAt;
        }
        Now em.remove(product) executes the UPDATE SQL, not a DELETE.
        And every SELECT Hibernate generates for Product automatically gets AND deleted_at IS NULL appended —
            in findById(), findAll(), JOIN fetches, everything. You never write the condition manually.
        productRepo.delete(product);
        // SQL: UPDATE products SET deleted_at = NOW() WHERE id = ?
        productRepo.findAll();
        // SQL: SELECT * FROM products WHERE deleted_at IS NULL   ← @Where applied automatically
        productRepo.findById(42L);
        // SQL: SELECT * FROM products WHERE id = 42 AND deleted_at IS NULL
        The @Where clause is baked into Hibernate's generated SQL at the mapping level, so it cannot be bypassed accidentally.
  B.  @FilterDef + @Filter (switchable filter):
        @Where is always-on. Hibernate @Filter is a named filter you can enable/disable per session — 
        useful when you need to temporarily see deleted records (admin panel, audit screen):
            @Entity
            @FilterDef(
                name = "deletedFilter",
                parameters = @ParamDef(name = "isDeleted", type = Boolean.class)
            )
            @Filter(name = "deletedFilter", condition = "deleted = :isDeleted")
            public class Product {
                // ...
                private boolean deleted = false;
            }
   Enable/disable the filter on the current session:
        @Service
        public class ProductService {
            @PersistenceContext
            private EntityManager em;
            @Transactional(readOnly = true)
            public List<Product> findActive() {
                // Enable filter for this session — only non-deleted rows returned
                em.unwrap(Session.class)
                  .enableFilter("deletedFilter")
                  .setParameter("isDeleted", false);
                return productRepo.findAll();
            }
            @Transactional(readOnly = true)
            public List<Product> findDeleted() {
                // Same filter, different parameter value — returns only deleted
                em.unwrap(Session.class)
                  .enableFilter("deletedFilter")
                  .setParameter("isDeleted", true);
                return productRepo.findAll();
            }
            @Transactional(readOnly = true)
            public List<Product> findAllIncludingDeleted() {
                // Filter NOT enabled — returns everything
                return productRepo.findAll();
            }
        }
    C.Spring Data JPA @SQLRestriction (Hibernate 6+ / Spring Boot 3+)
        @Where was deprecated in Hibernate 6. 
        The replacement is @SQLRestriction:
                  @Entity
                  @SQLRestriction("deleted_at IS NULL")   // same effect as @Where, new name
                  public class Product { ... }
                  @SQLDelete(sql = "UPDATE products SET deleted_at = NOW() WHERE id = ?")
        Soft delete with Spring Data: @NoRepositoryBean base
              For a reusable soft-delete base across all your entities:
                    @MappedSuperclass
                    @SQLDelete(sql = "UPDATE #{#entityName} SET deleted = true WHERE id = ?")
                    @SQLRestriction("deleted = false")
                    public abstract class SoftDeletableEntity {
                        @Id @GeneratedValue
                        private Long id;
                        @Column(nullable = false)
                        private boolean deleted = false;
                        @Column
                        private LocalDateTime deletedAt;
                        @PreRemove
                        void onRemove() {
                            this.deletedAt = LocalDateTime.now();
                        }
                    }
                    // All entities that extend this get soft-delete for free
                    @Entity
                    public class Product extends SoftDeletableEntity {
                        private String name;
                        // no delete boilerplate needed
                    }
        Finding soft-deleted records when you need them
            Since @SQLRestriction/@Where is applied globally to all Hibernate-generated SQL,
                you cannot bypass it with a JPQL or Spring Data query — Hibernate appends the clause regardless. 
            The only way to bypass it is with a native SQL query:
                   @Query(value = "SELECT * FROM products WHERE deleted_at IS NOT NULL", nativeQuery = true)
                    List<Product> findAllDeleted();
                    // Or use a separate EntityManager with native query for an admin restore screen:
                    @Transactional
                    public void restore(Long id) {
                        em.createNativeQuery("UPDATE products SET deleted_at = NULL, deleted = false WHERE id = :id")
                          .setParameter("id", id)
                          .executeUpdate();
                    }
5.  Java Message Service (JMS) 
    It is a Java API for sending messages between systems asynchronously.
      👉 Instead of direct communication: Service A → Service B (tight coupling ❌)
      👉 Use messaging: Service A → Message Queue → Service B (loose coupling ✅)

  What does “Asynchronous” mean? Sender does NOT wait for receiver
    Synchronous (REST style) -Service A → Service B → Response (wait)
        ❌ Blocking
        ❌ Slower under load
    Asynchronous (JMS) - Service A → Queue → (continues immediately)
                        ↓
                     Service B processes later
    
        ✔ Non-blocking
        ✔ Faster
        ✔ Decoupled
    jmsTemplate.convertAndSend("orderQueue", order);
    System.out.println("Order sent"); // runs immediately👉 No waiting for consumer

  Why JMS?
        Decouples systems
        Enables async processing
        Improves scalability
        Handles high load
 
  JMS Architecture
    Producer → Message Broker → Consumer
    🔹 1. Producer -Sends message
    🔹 2. Consumer - Receives message
    🔹 3. Message - Data being sent
    🔹 4. Destination -Where message goes Queue/Topic
    🔹 5. Message Broker -  Manages messages like ActiveMQ/RabbitMQ

   Message Types:
      🔹 TextMessage -"Hello World"
      🔹 ObjectMessage-Serializable object
      🔹 MapMessage - Key-value pairs
      🔹 BytesMessage -Binary data
  
  Messaging Models
      🔹 1. Queue (Point-to-Point) :Producer → Queue → ONE Consumer   
                          ✔ One consumer gets message
                          ✔ Load balancing
      🔹 2. Topic (Publish-Subscribe) : Producer → Topic → MANY Consumers
                          ✔ All subscribers receive message
  JMS with Spring:
    In the Spring Framework, JMS is simplified using: JmsTemplate  Like JdbcTemplate (for DB)
      🔹 Sending Message
            @Autowired
            private JmsTemplate jmsTemplate;
      
            jmsTemplate.convertAndSend("queue", "Hello JMS");
      🔹 Receiving Message
            @JmsListener(destination = "queue")
            public void receive(String message) {
                System.out.println(message);
            }
      Internal Working: convertAndSend → MessageConverter → Broker → Listener → Method execution
      Message ConversionL Spring converts Java object ↔ JMS message
            jmsTemplate.convertAndSend("queue", user);  ✔ Automatically serialized

    Transactions in JMS👉 Ensure message reliability
        @Transactional
        public void send() {
            jmsTemplate.convertAndSend("queue", "msg");
        }
        ✔ If transaction fails → message not sent
    
    Handling Timeouts in JMS
      Timeouts can happen when: Waiting for message, Broker delay and Consumer slow
      🔹 A. Receive Timeout - jmsTemplate.setReceiveTimeout(5000); // 5 seconds 👉 If no message → returns null
      🔹 B. Request-Reply Timeout - If using request-response pattern: jmsTemplate.setReceiveTimeout(3000);
      🔹 C. Connection Timeout - Configured in broker/client: ActiveMQ connection URL/ ConnectionFactory config
      Best Practices :Set proper timeout values, Avoid infinite waits and  Use retry mechanism

    What if Queue / Broker is NOT UP?
    ❌ Problem :App → JMS → Broker DOWN → Exception
     Handling Strategies
        ✔ 1. Retry Mechanism
              try {
                  jmsTemplate.convertAndSend("queue", msg);
              } catch (Exception e) {
                  // retry logic
              }
        Use: RetryTemplate (Spring),  Custom retry loop
        ✔ 2. Circuit Breaker (Advanced) 👉 Stop sending temporarily Tools: Resilience4j
        ✔ 3. Message Persistence👉 If broker is up but consumer down: ✔ Messages stored in broker ✔ Delivered later 
        ✔ 4. Failover Configuration: For brokers like ActiveMQ: failover:(tcp://host1:61616,tcp://host2:61616) ✔ Switches to backup broker
        ✔ 5. Dead Letter Queue (DLQ): 👉 Failed messages go here : queue → failure → DLQ ✔ Prevents data loss    
        ✔ 6. Logging & Alerting ✔ Monitor broker health ✔ Send alerts
    
     Acknowledgement Modes👉 Defines when message is considered successfully consumed
      🔹 1. AUTO_ACKNOWLEDGE- Session.AUTO_ACKNOWLEDGE 
                  ✔ Automatically acknowledged after processing
                  Receive → Process → Auto ACK
                  ⚠️ Risk If failure during processing → message lost
      🔹 2. CLIENT_ACKNOWLEDGE - Session.CLIENT_ACKNOWLEDGE
                  ✔ Manual acknowledgment
                  message.acknowledge();
                  Receive → Process → ACK manually
                  ✔ Advantage- Better control, Retry possible
      🔹 3. DUPS_OK_ACKNOWLEDGE -Session.DUPS_OK_ACKNOWLEDGE
                  ✔ Lazy acknowledgment
                  May deliver duplicates
                  Faster performance
                  ⚠️ Requirement👉 Consumer must handle duplicates
      🔹 4. TRANSACTED SESSION 
                  session.commit();
                  session.rollback();
                  Receive →Process →Commit → ACK
                  Rollback → message redelivered
                  ✔ Best for reliability
                  Ensures no data loss
                  Supports rollback
  Delivery Modes:
  🔹 Persistent - ✔ Saved to disk✔ Reliable
  🔹 Non-Persistent -✔ Faster ❌ Risk of loss
  
  🔥 Real-Time Example
  Order System: Order Service → Queue → Email Service
      ✔ Decoupled
      ✔ Async
  
  ⚠️ Common Problems
  ❗ Duplicate messages👉 Need idempotent handling
  ❗ Message loss 👉 Use persistent mode
  ❗ Ordering issues 👉 Depends on queue
  
  1. Is JMS synchronous? ❌ No → async
  2. Queue vs Topic?✔ Queue → one consumer✔ Topic → multiple
  3. What is JmsTemplate? ✔ Helper class
  4. What is broker? ✔ Message manager
  5. Does JMS guarantee delivery? ✔ Yes (with persistent mode)


